message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
title: "No Single Safety Gate: Distributed Routing of Harm-Refusal in a Mixture-of-Experts Language Model"
abstract: >-
  A mixture-of-experts (MoE) language model routes each token to a few experts
  through a discrete router, which makes it natural to ask whether harm-refusal is
  owned by a single "safety expert." We probe this in base Qwen3.5-35B-A3B with
  all-layer router capture under greedy decoding. The generation-side routing
  difference on token-matched redflag versus benign prompts is led by one expert
  (173 at layer 25), but a finance-versus-consequence control shows the broader
  signal is a real-world-consequence and duty cluster, separable from finance-domain
  experts. Suppressing expert 173 with a router bias collapses its routed mass
  dose-dependently, yet the model never produces a harmful completion on the prompt
  set: routing reallocates to sibling experts and the refusals persist. In this model
  and setup, refusal is carried by a distributed expert cluster with no single gate.
  An exploratory case study (n=6 and n=12, single greedy trajectories).
